Easy

This part is a comparison between sgdnet and glmnet, in terms of the time and loss for gaussian, logistic and multinomial families. I use the loss function with elastic-net penalty as follows, where \(\lambda = 1\) is the parameter for lasso penalty (for R code).

  • Gaussian: \(\frac{1}{2}\left \| \boldsymbol{XW} -\boldsymbol{y} \right \| ^{2} + \lambda \alpha \left \| \boldsymbol{W} \right \|_{1} + \lambda (1- \alpha) \left \| \boldsymbol{W} \right \|_{2}\).

  • Logistic regression:
    • Loss = \(\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n} \rho_{W}(\boldsymbol{X_{i}},{y{i}}) + \lambda \alpha \left \| \boldsymbol{W} \right \|_{1} + \lambda (1- \alpha) \left \| \boldsymbol{W} \right \|_{2}\);
    • \(\rho_{W}(\boldsymbol{X},{y}) = -\boldsymbol{y}(\sum_{j=1}^{p+1} \boldsymbol{w}_{j}\boldsymbol{x}^{(j)}) + log(1+ exp(\sum_{j=1}^{p+1} \boldsymbol{w}_{j}\boldsymbol{x}^{(j)}))\).
  • Multinomial families:
    • Loss = \(\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n} \rho_{W}(\boldsymbol{X_{i}},{y{i}}) + \lambda \alpha \sum_{k=1}^{c} \left \| \boldsymbol{W^{(k)}} \right \|_{1} + \lambda (1-\alpha) \sum_{k=1}^{c} \left \| \boldsymbol{W^{(k)}} \right \|_{2}\);
    • \(\rho_{W}(\boldsymbol{X},{y}) = -(\sum_{j=1}^{p+1} \sum_{k=1}^{c} \boldsymbol{y_{l}} \, \boldsymbol{w}^{(k)}_{j} \boldsymbol{x}^{(j)}) + log(1+ exp(\sum_{j=1}^{p+1}\sum_{k=1}^{c} \boldsymbol{w}^{(k)}_{j} \boldsymbol{x}^{(j)}))\), where \(\boldsymbol{y}_{l} = I(\boldsymbol{y}=l), l = 1,...,c\).

Test is based on dataset abalone and cadata, which are from LIBSVM. abalone contains 4177 observations and 8 features. cadata contains 20,640 observations and 8 features. The response variables for both are continuous. For logistic and multinomial models, the response variable is transformed into categorical data according to median and \(1^{st}\), \(2^{nd}\) and \(3^{rd}\) quantiles. Here I take a step size \(\gamma = 1/n.obs\). In Figure 1 and 2, loss objectives are collected at a sequence of runtime, when two function adopts a same stopping criteria. The first row of each figure are results with lasso penalty and the second with ridge penalty.(My R code)

Median

This part use RcppEigen to write a class that defines the lasso (l1) penalty. Here we only have lasso terms and set \(\alpha=1\), and \(\lambda = \frac{1}{n}\) for regularization strength, and \(\gamma > 0\) is the step size. The proximal mapping of a convex function \(h\) is defined as

\[prox_{h}(x) = arg \underset{u}{min} \left ( h(u) + \frac{1}{2} \left \| u-x \right \|^{2}_{2} \right )\]

For \(h(\boldsymbol{\omega})\) = \(\left \| \boldsymbol{\omega} \right \| _{1}\) as our lasso penalty, the proximal mapping of \(h\) is denoted as \(prox_{h}(\boldsymbol{\omega})\), which is specified as `soft - threshould for lasso. For each entry of \(\omega\)

\[ prox_{h}(\boldsymbol{\omega_{i}}) = \left\{\begin{matrix} \omega_{i} - 1 & \omega_{i} \geq 1 \\ 0 & |\omega_{i}| \leq 1\\ \omega_{i} + 1 & \omega_{i} \leq -1 \end{matrix}\right.\]

In iteration \(k+1\), we first conduct the gradient descent step \[\boldsymbol{\omega}^{\frac{1}{2}+k} \leftarrow \boldsymbol{\omega}^{k} - \gamma \nabla f(\boldsymbol{\omega}^{k}) \, \, (*)\] Then update \(\boldsymbol{\omega}^{k+1} = prox_{\gamma h}(\boldsymbol{\omega}^{\frac{1}{2}+k}) = arg \underset{u}{min} \left \{ \lambda \alpha |u|_{1} + \frac{1}{2} \left \| u- \boldsymbol{\omega}^{\frac{1}{2}+k} \right \|^{2}_{2} \right \}\) following the definition. Then the updated \(\boldsymbol{\omega}^{k+1}\) has each entry equals to \(\frac{\omega_{j}}{|\omega_{j}|} max \{0, |\omega_{j} - \alpha \lambda|\}\), where \(\omega_{j}\) is the corresponding entry in \(\boldsymbol{\omega}^{\frac{1}{2}+k}\). The loss is straightforward to be evaluated as \(\lambda \alpha \left \| \boldsymbol{\omega^{k}} \right \| _{1}\).

In l1.h, we define the class.

// [[Rcpp::depends(RcppEigen)]]
#include <RcppEigen.h>
#include <Rcpp.h>
using namespace Rcpp;
using namespace RcppEigen;
#ifndef L1_H
#define L1_H
class l1{
public:
  l1(Eigen::MatrixXd W_, double alpha_, double rate_);
  Eigen::MatrixXd prox();
  double loss();
  
private:
  Eigen::MatrixXd W;
  double alpha;
  double rate;
};
#endif

And the corresponding functions prox() and loss() are defined in SGD.cpp.

l1::l1(Eigen::MatrixXd W_, double alpha_, double rate_): 
  W(W_), alpha(alpha_), rate(rate_){}
Eigen::MatrixXd l1::prox(){
  int n = W.rows();
  Eigen::MatrixXd Wnew = W;
  double w = 0;
  double tmp = 0.0;
  for (int i=0; i<n; i++){
    w = W(i,0)/std::abs(W(i,0));
    tmp = W(i,0) - alpha*rate;
    if (tmp < 0){Wnew(i,0)=0;}
    else {Wnew(i,0) = tmp*w;}
  }
  return(Wnew);
}

double l1::loss(){
  int n = W.rows();
  double loss = 0.0;
  for (int i=0; i<n; i++){loss+=std::abs(W(i,0));}
  loss = loss * alpha *rate;
  return(loss);
}

For this question, we do not need to consider the step size \(\gamma\). An object is created using lasso \(\leftarrow\) new(l1, W, \(lambda\), \(\alpha\)), and its loss and proximal vector is returned by lasso$loss() and lasso$prox().

library(sgdtest)
W <- as.matrix(c(2.9579215,0.9848356))
lasso <- new(l1, W, 0.01, 1)
lasso$prox() # proximal operator(soft thresholing)
##           [,1]
## [1,] 2.9479215
## [2,] 0.9748356
lasso$loss() # evaluate the loss
## [1] 0.03942757

Hard

In the regular stochastic gradient descent algorithm, the equation \((*)\) becomes:

\[\boldsymbol{\omega}^{\frac{1}{2}+k} \leftarrow \boldsymbol{\omega}^{k} - \gamma \nabla f_{i}(\boldsymbol{\omega}^{k}), \, i \leftarrow U(1, n)\].

My function SGD(\(\boldsymbol{X}\),\(\boldsymbol{y}\),iter,\(\boldsymbol{\lambda}\),\(\boldsymbol{\alpha}\),\(\boldsymbol{\gamma}\)) is implemented in SGD.cpp of sgdtest. The parameter \(\boldsymbol{X}\) is a matrix including intercept terms, and \(\boldsymbol{y}\) is a one-column matrix. The stopping occurs when the algorithm is iterated up to number iter, with step length equals to \(\gamma\). And by setting \(\alpha=1\), the function is regularized by lasso penalty with regularization strength \(\lambda\). The following code is the algorithm part of my package sgdtest.

// [[Rcpp::export]]
Eigen::MatrixXd SGD(const Eigen::MatrixXd & X, 
                     const Eigen::MatrixXd & y, 
                     const int & iter, 
                     const double & rate, 
                     const double & alpha,
                     const double & size)
{
  /**Intialization*/
  int n = y.size();
  int m = X.cols();
  int idx = 0;
  Eigen::MatrixXd error(1,1);
  Eigen::MatrixXd W(m,1);
  Eigen::MatrixXd Gradient(m,1);
  error.fill(0.0);
  W.fill(0.0);
  Gradient.fill(0.0);
  
  /**Iteration*/  
  for(int i=0; i<iter; i++){
    /**Generate random number*/
    Rcpp::IntegerVector pool = Rcpp::seq(0, n-1);
    std::random_shuffle(pool.begin(), pool.end());
    idx = pool[0];
    
    /**Gradient Descent*/
    error = X.row(idx)*W - y.row(idx);
    Gradient = X.row(idx).transpose()*error;
    W = W - Gradient * size;
    
    /**lasso penality*/
    if (alpha != 0.0){
      l1 s = l1(W, alpha, rate);
      W = s.prox();
    }
  }
  return W;
}

A simple case shows that my package actually works. I simulate \(1000\) sample \(\boldsymbol{X} \sim \boldsymbol{U}(-5, 5)\) and set \(\boldsymbol{y} = \boldsymbol{X} + \boldsymbol{\epsilon} + 3\) where \(\boldsymbol{\epsilon} \sim \boldsymbol{N}(0,1)\). For lasso penalty, I use set parameters as SGD(,,600, 0.001, 1, 0.005)$ And this is a comparison among the fitted coefficients from sgdtest with and without lasso penalty, the lm( ) function which is unbiased, and the results from sgdnet and glmnet with lasso penalty.

set.seed(0)
x <- runif(1000, -5, 5)
y <- x + rnorm(1000) + 3
X <- matrix(cbind(1, matrix(x)), nrow = 1000)
y <- matrix(y, nrow = 1000)
qr <- lm(y ~ x)$coefficients
my_lasso <- SGD(X,y, 600, 0.001, 1, 0.005)
my <- SGD(X,y, 600, 0.001, 0, 0.005)
sgd<- sgdnet(X, y, family="gaussian", intercept = TRUE, lambda=0.001, alpha=1, standardize=FALSE)
glm<- glmnet(X, y, family="gaussian", intercept = TRUE, lambda=0.001, alpha=1, standardize=FALSE)
sgd_coef <- sgd$beta
glm_coef <- glm$beta
sgd_coef[1] <- sgd$a0
glm_coef[1] <- glm$a0

result <- cbind(qr, my, my_lasso, sgd_coef, glm_coef)
rownames(result) <- c("intercept","x")
colnames(result) <- c("lm()","SGD without l1","SGD with l1","sgdnet","glmnet")
print(result)
## 2 x 5 sparse Matrix of class "dgCMatrix"
##                lm() SGD without l1 SGD with l1    sgdnet    glmnet
## intercept 2.9579215      2.8114729   2.5770281 2.9581090 2.9579223
## x         0.9848356      0.9229309   0.9430161 0.9847002 0.9847155

And we can see that the loss is decreasing as the SGD( ) runs more iterations, the simulation code can be viewed HERE.

################################################################
#loss function for my package
loss <- function(w, X, y, alpha, lambda){
  # X should contain the intercept column
  w <- matrix(w) # get coef
  sum((X%*%w - y)^2)/2 + lambda*alpha*sum(abs(w))
}
################################################################
# test
loss_my <- rep(0,500)

for (iter in 1:500){
  my_lasso <- SGD(X,y, iter, 0.001, 1, 0.005)
  loss_my[iter] <- loss(my_lasso, X, y, 1, 0.001)
}

plot(loss_my, type="l", main="loss over iteration of SGD()", xlab="number of iteration", ylab="loss")
